Title: The Overstory
Author: Richard Powers
My Review:
good things first: i like a lot of the book’s ideas, and it certainly has its fair share of good quotes. however, it is not my cup of tea because of one main issue: too. many. words!

yes, i admire the author’s love for and knowledge of trees. if anything, i also wish to one day have a similar passion for life. nevertheless, i don’t think that any meaningful paragraph has to be accompanied by an even longer one describing a variety of trees in incredibly cryptic language. yes, trees are old and magnificent - the point only needs to be made once.

additionally, i find the character development a bit lacking. the only stories i find make sense are nick and neelay’s, while the leap of faith to loving trees of other characters are rather tenuous. in other words, i can’t quite grasp or empathize with why they did what they did.

finally, the thing that pushed me over the edge on this one is the rambling final part about “the learners”. this might be incredibly geeky but the portrayal of AI or technology as these scary beings that may one day enslave mankind and destroy trees are… unrealistic, to say the least. this is not to say that technology is always good, but if you’re going to include it in, i feel like it deserves a more nuanced representation than just to scare people off. instead of long winded and unnecessary paragraphs about how these learners are slowly becoming sentient (which is absolutely wrong by the way), how about exploring how technology can help? how it’s harming? what does it mean to be human, to be sentient?

so yeah, not a big fan. technology boogie manning is always a red flag for me, and the lengthy prose does not make this a quick read. if you don’t like the couple first chapters, you’re probably not gonna like the rest any better.

Title: Design as Art
Author: Bruno Munari
My Review:
a couple of random takeaways:
- the most important thing about design is function: a thing should be designed according to how it is used. stripping down all superfluous elements that don’t serve the function can reveal the core of a design.
- visual language is always changing itself and affecting our behaviour. good use of visual language such as symbols can tell stories and evoke feelings like poetry.
- art in general should strive to become more democratic.
- all components of a design should live harmoniously next to one another.
- a good designer should understand the intrinsic characters of important components like type, color, or composition, as well as how viewers react to them in the real world environment.
- a design depends as much on its own merits as its surroundings.
- studying and understanding nature and mundane objects can inspire art.
- the core of creating art is play - experimenting, asking “what-ifs”, seeing things from weird vantage points, messing with forms and time and space and all things considered not to be messed with.
- art should change its material and form to adapt to and reflect the times.
- good art should be intuitive.

Title: Homo Deus: A History of Tomorrow
Author: Yuval Noah Harari
My Review:
to be honest, i am rather disappointed. the beginning of it was fine: insightful and compelling, just like Sapiens. however, it really got off track once it started talking about algorithms, data, and technology in general. i feel like that section of the book meant to evoke emotional responses more than inform, and quite a lot of the content can mislead people about the true nature of technologies.

for instance, Yuval dedicates an entire chapter to talk about how people will just give control to algorithms because they’re always more accurate. this ignores the fact that there are biases embedded in the algorithms in the first place that make them potentially wrong. because algorithms are created BY HUMANS. overall, the book seems to paint a future where humans have little ownership and ignore the myriad of ethical and practical discussions currently going on about ML and AI.

also, if technology is going to depower us that much, i expected Yuval to spend more time delineating who is guiding technology, how can we exert influence and take control of our own future too, what skills we can learn to empower ourselves, etc.

overall, this may be one of the times when storytelling triumphes over substance.

Title: In Praise of Shadows
Author: Jun'ichirō Tanizaki
Additional Authors: Edward G. Seidensticker, Thomas J. Harper, Charles Moore
My Review:
*things i like about this:
1. it made an interesting point about the distinct aesthetics of the east: silence, dimness, subtlety.
2. it pointed out the significant bearing of technology on culture and vice versa.
3. i swear there was a third point but i just forgot it... i'll get back here when i remember lol
*things i do not like about this:
1. in discussions about aesthetics, it is good sense to ask who gets to decide what beauty is. in this case, there is an abstract "we" deciding that to curate feminine beauty, "we" must put them away in dark rooms and dye their teeth black; "we" must dress and exhibit properly. the fetishisation and alienation is clear: "Our ancestors cut off the brightness on the land from above and created a world of shadows, and far in the depths of it they placed woman, marking her the whitest of beings." does this imply somehow that our ancestors do not include women?
2. there are also instances of internalised racism - yellow skin is deemed "dirty", and the consequent dizzying chain of argument seems alarmingly sympathetic of anti-black sentiments.
after all, a readable piece of work. however, one must be very careful in reading it.
